00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:16.230
students and researchers
of several institutes

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:19.610
from different countries,
are working independently

00:03:19.610 --> 00:03:21.800
towards the same goal.

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:26.160
This was going to be a sleepless
night for the searchers,

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:30.040
the working group of
the CMS experiment

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:33.490
at the Large Hadron Collider
of European Organization

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:37.590
for Nuclear Research,
searching for the Higgs boson

00:03:37.590 --> 00:03:40.120
through its decay
into two photons.

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:43.850
About one quarter century
ago before this June

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:49.270
night, my life started in
19-- one of the Asian capitals

00:03:49.270 --> 00:03:51.020
in China.

00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:53.250
My name is Mingming.

00:03:53.250 --> 00:03:56.740
In Chinese, Ming
equals to [INAUDIBLE],

00:03:56.740 --> 00:03:59.070
both associated with light.

00:03:59.070 --> 00:04:02.010
Since the particle of
light is called photon,

00:04:02.010 --> 00:04:04.390
if you want you can also
call me photon photon.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:09.940
I don't think my parents
gave me this name in order

00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:12.910
to encourage me to search for
Higgs boson through its decay

00:04:12.910 --> 00:04:15.900
into two photons,
because my parents have

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:18.550
no idea what is a Higgs boson.

00:04:18.550 --> 00:04:20.974
But I do thank
them for giving me

00:04:20.974 --> 00:04:23.650
a happy childhood with
little constraint,

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:27.620
and letting me grow
freely into myself.

00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:30.980
When I was 13 years
old, every weekday

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:34.440
I walked between my home
and my middle school,

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:38.540
40 minutes in the morning,
40 minutes in the afternoon.

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:42.450
On the road, I think about
various kinds of questions.

00:04:42.450 --> 00:04:44.940
What score would I get
for the [INAUDIBLE] exam?

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:46.960
What to eat tonight?

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:51.940
I usually ran out of such daily
life questions about halfway,

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:54.140
and ended up
thinking about, what

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:56.260
is the fundamental
nature of the world?

00:04:56.260 --> 00:04:58.460
Why do we do this?

00:04:58.460 --> 00:05:01.530
I don't think I
reached any conclusions

00:05:01.530 --> 00:05:06.220
on those profound questions
on that road at that time.

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:09.980
But I suspected thinking
about those questions

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:14.740
somehow transported me
to a particular space

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:16.227
at a particular time.

00:05:16.227 --> 00:05:19.260
To unblind the search
results of the Higgs

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:22.050
boson along with my colleagues.

00:05:22.050 --> 00:05:24.990
And this result is
crucial to answer

00:05:24.990 --> 00:05:29.210
one of the fundamental questions
of the particle physics--

00:05:29.210 --> 00:05:32.050
what is origin of mass?

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:35.860
At this moment, the standard
model of particle physics

00:05:35.860 --> 00:05:39.050
has survived all the
experimental tests

00:05:39.050 --> 00:05:43.040
since its foundation
about a half century ago

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.450
The standard model is
a theory endeavoring

00:05:46.450 --> 00:05:52.150
to describe all matter and
all forces in the universe

00:05:52.150 --> 00:05:54.720
except for gravity.

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:57.800
[INAUDIBLE] are
fundamental particles.

00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:00.590
How fundamental is fundamental?

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:03.870
Is an atom considered as
a fundamental particle?

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:08.490
The answer is no, because when
we look closely into an atom,

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:11.090
we see it is actually made
up of a particle called

00:06:11.090 --> 00:06:15.400
proton, surrounded by another
particle called the electron.

00:06:15.400 --> 00:06:18.160
And when we look
further into the proton,

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:22.410
we see it is made up of three
particles called quarks.

00:06:22.410 --> 00:06:27.850
However, when we look as
closely as we can into the quark

00:06:27.850 --> 00:06:31.680
and electron, we do not
see any subparticle inside,

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:34.430
and electrons and
quarks are considered

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:37.890
as fundamental particles.

00:06:37.890 --> 00:06:42.495
According to the standard model,
all the fundamental particles

00:06:42.495 --> 00:06:48.190
are originally massless, like
photons, the particle carrying

00:06:48.190 --> 00:06:52.490
electromagnetic force, also
known as a particle of light,

00:06:52.490 --> 00:06:57.430
whose speed in space-time is
the maximum allowed speed,

00:06:57.430 --> 00:06:59.800
the speed of light.

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:04.180
However, a hypothetical
field permitting over space

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:09.350
and through time, and
this lightness of being,

00:07:09.350 --> 00:07:13.900
and it interacts with
the fundamental particles

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:19.010
like water dragging down the
fish from the swimming of speed

00:07:19.010 --> 00:07:20.210
of light.

00:07:20.210 --> 00:07:23.810
And it gives mass to the
fundamental particles,

00:07:23.810 --> 00:07:28.000
which leads to the
formation of structures--

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.480
the stars, Earth, mountains,
and we human beings.

00:07:35.080 --> 00:07:38.860
To prove the existence of
this field generating mass

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:43.520
that underlies other
existence, the observation

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:47.750
of the rip of the field, that
last undetected fundamental

00:07:47.750 --> 00:07:53.700
particle, also called a
Higgs boson, was a key.

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:56.940
Generations of experimental
particle physicists

00:07:56.940 --> 00:08:01.640
have been searching
for the Higgs boson,

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:05.600
but no evidence is found.

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:10.920
The mass of the Higgs boson
is unknown except for a rough

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:12.990
larger bound, upper bound.

00:08:12.990 --> 00:08:17.880
And the possibility of low
Higgs mass is excluded.

00:08:17.880 --> 00:08:21.990
Why the Higgs boson is so
difficult to be detected?

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:24.415
First, it is very
difficult to be produced.

00:08:27.130 --> 00:08:29.560
The Higgs boson is
expected to be produced

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:32.230
from the collision between
a pair of particles,

00:08:32.230 --> 00:08:36.340
for example protons, where
the original particles are

00:08:36.340 --> 00:08:39.059
destroyed, and their
energies are converted

00:08:39.059 --> 00:08:42.070
to the mass of a Higgs boson.

00:08:42.070 --> 00:08:43.880
The Higgs boson
has a large mass.

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:48.180
That means it needs large
energy to be produced.

00:08:48.180 --> 00:08:51.090
And even if energy is
enough, the production rate

00:08:51.090 --> 00:08:53.550
of the Higgs boson
is extremely low,

00:08:53.550 --> 00:08:56.770
about one out of
billions of collisions.

00:08:56.770 --> 00:08:59.495
Therefore a very
powerful collider

00:08:59.495 --> 00:09:03.790
is needed to provide
intense proton beams

00:09:03.790 --> 00:09:08.110
and bring them into
connections at a speed

00:09:08.110 --> 00:09:10.900
almost the speed
of light in order

00:09:10.900 --> 00:09:16.210
to create the Higgs boson in
a reasonable amount of time.

00:09:16.210 --> 00:09:20.570
Second, even if the
Higgs boson is produced,

00:09:20.570 --> 00:09:26.100
it decays immediately into
different types of particles,

00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:28.320
and only these
decaying particles

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:32.300
can be detected given a
comprehensive detector

00:09:32.300 --> 00:09:36.220
to identify different
types of particles

00:09:36.220 --> 00:09:40.030
and measure their energies
and moving directions.

00:09:40.030 --> 00:09:43.290
An enormous amount of
background collisions,

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:45.730
which does not produce
the Higgs boson,

00:09:45.730 --> 00:09:50.060
but the particles either
exactly the same or very similar

00:09:50.060 --> 00:09:51.820
to the Higgs decay.

00:09:51.820 --> 00:09:55.530
And the physicists have to
analyze the data collected

00:09:55.530 --> 00:09:58.805
from millions of
billions of collisions

00:09:58.805 --> 00:10:02.920
in order to illuminate
the statistical evidence

00:10:02.920 --> 00:10:05.120
of the Higgs boson.

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:09.850
Finally, the Large Hadron
Collider is constructed.

00:10:09.850 --> 00:10:14.090
The Large Hadron Collider
is a 27-kilometer ring

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:19.230
underneath the area between
Geneva Lake and Jura Mountains,

00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:23.650
and it is designed to
collide two beams of protons

00:10:23.650 --> 00:10:31.190
at energies up to 14 TeV,
where one TeV equals 1,000 GeV,

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:35.590
and 1 GeV is about
the mass of a proton.

00:10:35.590 --> 00:10:37.820
This collision
energy if seven times

00:10:37.820 --> 00:10:44.120
that of the previous-- highest
energy of the previous most

00:10:44.120 --> 00:10:45.980
powerful collider.

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:48.450
And the construction of
the Large Hadron Collider,

00:10:48.450 --> 00:10:53.560
along with its two largest
experiments, CMS and Atlas,

00:10:53.560 --> 00:10:57.120
essentially are
proving or excluding

00:10:57.120 --> 00:11:00.870
the existence of
the Higgs boson.

00:11:00.870 --> 00:11:05.080
Both experiments have a
giant cylindrical detector,

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:11.810
thousands of meters in
length and half that length

00:11:11.810 --> 00:11:13.640
in diameter.

00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:18.670
And a collaboration of thousands
of physicists and engineers

00:11:18.670 --> 00:11:22.240
are all over the world.

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:27.330
Each experiment is to conduct
an independent Higgs search

00:11:27.330 --> 00:11:30.750
through particle search
channels over a wide range

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:33.000
of possible Higgs mass.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.660
And each search channel is
to search for the Higgs boson

00:11:36.660 --> 00:11:40.380
through a particular
type of the Higgs decay,

00:11:40.380 --> 00:11:45.060
which is sensitive to a certain
range of the Higgs mass.

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:49.260
In 2011, when the Large
Hadron Collider just

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:52.070
ramped up the rate of
proton-proton collisions

00:11:52.070 --> 00:11:55.930
at the energy of 7
TeV, I came to CERN

00:11:55.930 --> 00:11:59.560
to work on my PhD thesis,
searching for the Higgs boson

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:01.610
through the two-proton channel.

00:12:01.610 --> 00:12:05.730
Well, after five main search
channels of the Higgs boson,

00:12:05.730 --> 00:12:10.800
along with my teammates from
MIT and other colleagues

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:14.150
within the Higgs to two-photon
working group of the CMS

00:12:14.150 --> 00:12:17.040
experiment, by
analyzing the data

00:12:17.040 --> 00:12:19.000
collected from
this sim detector.

00:12:21.610 --> 00:12:27.460
This plot shows you a collision
event producing two photons

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:32.860
and caught by the detector
where the blue cylindrical area

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:36.310
represents the detector, called
electromagnetic calorimeter

00:12:36.310 --> 00:12:38.720
made of tens of
thousands of crystals,

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:42.090
and the two red bars
represent the energy deposit

00:12:42.090 --> 00:12:43.465
of the photons
into the detector.

00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:50.780
The two-photons channel looks
for two energetic photons

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:53.310
from the Higgs decay.

00:12:53.310 --> 00:12:55.890
And it is one of the
most promising channels

00:12:55.890 --> 00:13:00.590
for the Higgs discovery when
the Higgs mas is relatively low,

00:13:00.590 --> 00:13:04.940
between 110 GeV and the 150 GeV.

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:09.270
Thanks to the electromagnetic
calorimeter, photons

00:13:09.270 --> 00:13:11.510
can be clearly identified.

00:13:11.510 --> 00:13:13.400
Furthermore, their
energies could

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:16.910
be mirrored with excellent
resolution, from which

00:13:16.910 --> 00:13:20.530
a quantity called two-photon
mass can be reconstructed

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:23.350
precisely for each photon pair.

00:13:23.350 --> 00:13:30.130
And this allows us constructing
a characteristic spectrum

00:13:30.130 --> 00:13:34.230
of the two-photon mass of
the identified photon pairs,

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:38.070
as shown on the right plot.

00:13:38.070 --> 00:13:42.700
In this spectrum, a signal peak
due to a Higgs boson centered

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:45.970
on the Higgs mass, with
its width determined

00:13:45.970 --> 00:13:48.220
to by the two-photon
mass resolution,

00:13:48.220 --> 00:13:51.860
will sit on top of a
smoothly falling slope

00:13:51.860 --> 00:13:56.710
of the background, which
would give persuasive evidence

00:13:56.710 --> 00:14:01.000
if the Higgs boson exists.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:06.180
Despite the appealing
feature of the signal peak,

00:14:06.180 --> 00:14:10.500
the Higgs boson actually
does not quite frequently

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:13.630
decay to two photons.

00:14:13.630 --> 00:14:16.280
How rare is a two-photon decay?

00:14:16.280 --> 00:14:20.860
It is about one out of hundreds
of the decay of already

00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:22.990
rarely produced Higgs bosons.

00:14:22.990 --> 00:14:26.530
So the great challenge
facing this search channel

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:31.380
is to identify this small
peak from the large background

00:14:31.380 --> 00:14:32.900
underneath.

00:14:32.900 --> 00:14:37.020
Facing this challenge, we
developed nice strategy

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:40.290
to classify the photon pairs.

00:14:40.290 --> 00:14:43.250
The ones more likely
from the Higgs decay

00:14:43.250 --> 00:14:46.460
and have better
mass resolution are

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:49.930
selected into a
higher-ranking class, which

00:14:49.930 --> 00:14:53.490
will have a sharper peak
in the mass spectrum

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:58.330
and add more sensitivity
to the Higgs signal.

00:14:58.330 --> 00:15:03.280
Finally, we extract the signal
by comparing the observed

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:08.690
spectra of all the classes
with models of expected signal

00:15:08.690 --> 00:15:11.860
plus background spectrum.

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:17.570
If any excess of the photon
pairs above the background

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:23.250
expectation is observed, we
estimate the significance

00:15:23.250 --> 00:15:28.430
of the excess, as shown
on the right plot.

00:15:28.430 --> 00:15:30.820
The black curve
shows a probability

00:15:30.820 --> 00:15:34.230
that the observed excess
is due to the fluctuation

00:15:34.230 --> 00:15:36.910
of the background.

00:15:36.910 --> 00:15:40.560
If the lowest
probability is about one

00:15:40.560 --> 00:15:46.190
out of 1,000, corresponding to a
significance about three sigma,

00:15:46.190 --> 00:15:49.650
we say there is evidence
of a new particle.

00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:54.960
And if the probability is
about dozens out of a million,

00:15:54.960 --> 00:15:56.740
corresponding to
four sigma, we say

00:15:56.740 --> 00:15:59.190
there's convincing evidence.

00:15:59.190 --> 00:16:04.480
And if the probability reaches
1 out of 3 and 1/2 million,

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:08.930
corresponding to five sigma,
we claim the discovery

00:16:08.930 --> 00:16:10.940
of a new particle.

00:16:10.940 --> 00:16:16.700
OK, it takes a couple minutes
to say, however years to do.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:19.790
In order to reach the
final mass spectrum,

00:16:19.790 --> 00:16:23.280
we need to go through
many steps in analysis

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:28.570
from the photon identification,
photon energy reconstruction,

00:16:28.570 --> 00:16:30.920
photon direction
of reconstruction,

00:16:30.920 --> 00:16:33.500
and the photon pair
classification.

00:16:33.500 --> 00:16:39.460
This plot gives you an example
of the observed mass spectrum

00:16:39.460 --> 00:16:41.980
from one of the classes.

00:16:41.980 --> 00:16:45.480
The black data points
show the observed number

00:16:45.480 --> 00:16:48.580
of pairs of photons
as a function

00:16:48.580 --> 00:16:50.680
of the two-photon mass.

00:16:50.680 --> 00:16:54.850
And the red curve is the
distribution of signal

00:16:54.850 --> 00:16:58.990
plus background fit
to the observed data.

00:16:58.990 --> 00:17:02.350
If the Higgs boson
exists, we would

00:17:02.350 --> 00:17:05.690
expect to see an
excess of photon pairs

00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:13.453
as shown like this data point
jumping from the background--

00:17:13.453 --> 00:17:14.619
smoothly falling background.

00:17:17.569 --> 00:17:20.760
By analyzing the 2011
data, we observed

00:17:20.760 --> 00:17:24.840
an excess of photon pairs above
the background expectation.

00:17:28.420 --> 00:17:30.830
Another channel in
the CMS experiment,

00:17:30.830 --> 00:17:33.790
the [INAUDIBLE] search channel,
also observed an excess,

00:17:33.790 --> 00:17:36.260
but not as significant.

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:39.260
And the combined excess
at the CMS experiment

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:44.070
is dominated by the excess
from the two-photon channel.

00:17:44.070 --> 00:17:46.530
A similar excess
is also observed

00:17:46.530 --> 00:17:49.650
at the Atlas
experiment, dominated

00:17:49.650 --> 00:17:53.260
by the excess of its
two-photon channel as well.

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:56.440
To determine the
source of this excess,

00:17:56.440 --> 00:17:58.680
whether it is from
the background

00:17:58.680 --> 00:18:04.510
fluctuation or a real signal,
the analysis of the 2012 data

00:18:04.510 --> 00:18:06.120
is critical.

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:13.070
We improved our analysis, and
we optimized it to accommodate

00:18:13.070 --> 00:18:16.590
the enhanced energy to 8 TeV.

00:18:16.590 --> 00:18:21.940
And to avoid any possibility to
bias the results-- for example,

00:18:21.940 --> 00:18:25.140
artificially create a
peak in a spectrum--

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:29.200
we do the analysis in a
strictly blind manner.

00:18:29.200 --> 00:18:32.240
That means we do not
look at the signal

00:18:32.240 --> 00:18:37.840
region in the mass spectrum
between 110 GeV to 150 GeV

00:18:37.840 --> 00:18:40.810
until our analysis is
fully fixed and verified.

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:46.420
And all the other Higgs
search channels also

00:18:46.420 --> 00:18:49.370
progressed under the blind.

00:18:49.370 --> 00:18:55.820
Finally, we reached this
night before June 15, 2012.

00:18:55.820 --> 00:18:59.720
In order to reach this night, we
had gone through many sleepless

00:18:59.720 --> 00:19:03.280
nights working on analysis
through the development

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:07.310
of different kinds of
components of the analysis,

00:19:07.310 --> 00:19:10.330
to multiple rounds
of producing results

00:19:10.330 --> 00:19:14.739
to keep updated with the
increased data and improved

00:19:14.739 --> 00:19:15.905
calibration of the detector.

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:22.550
We had multiple teams in
the Higgs two-photon working

00:19:22.550 --> 00:19:28.070
group, each team running an
independent analysis framework.

00:19:28.070 --> 00:19:33.660
Those teams had also gone though
constructive, while sometimes

00:19:33.660 --> 00:19:37.230
fierce competitions on
the analysis methods,

00:19:37.230 --> 00:19:41.450
but ultimately strove together
for the final results.

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:47.550
To finalize the analysis
for the unblinding

00:19:47.550 --> 00:19:50.390
and to synchronize
among different teams

00:19:50.390 --> 00:19:54.510
equals to a huge effort
of the entire group.

00:19:54.510 --> 00:19:57.140
And finally, two
teams synchronized

00:19:57.140 --> 00:19:59.380
to a satisfactory level.

00:19:59.380 --> 00:20:03.390
Each team was going to produce
a set of unblinded results

00:20:03.390 --> 00:20:05.480
to cross check.

00:20:05.480 --> 00:20:08.690
Among all the teams,
the MIT two-photon team

00:20:08.690 --> 00:20:12.740
is a small team known for
all coffee and no sleep.

00:20:12.740 --> 00:20:15.570
Our coffee machine
works so hard,

00:20:15.570 --> 00:20:17.370
and it was finally broken.

00:20:19.930 --> 00:20:22.480
As a result, our
proposed method was

00:20:22.480 --> 00:20:27.470
determined by the group as
the main analysis method.

00:20:27.470 --> 00:20:31.165
Besides the coffee machine,
working with me day and night

00:20:31.165 --> 00:20:33.550
are my teammates.

00:20:33.550 --> 00:20:37.240
So this guy with
the exploding hair

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:43.110
is Josh Bendavid, senior
graduate student from Canada.

00:20:43.110 --> 00:20:46.740
Josh effectively worked
24 hours every day.

00:20:46.740 --> 00:20:50.780
Whenever I needed discussion--
2:00 AM, 3:00 AM, 4:00 AM, 5:00

00:20:50.780 --> 00:20:56.570
AM, Josh is always there
online or on the phone,

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:59.360
and our conversations
can write a book

00:20:59.360 --> 00:21:05.170
about 1,000 pages all about
the search for the Higgs boson.

00:21:05.170 --> 00:21:10.070
And this guy, he looks very shy.

00:21:10.070 --> 00:21:14.420
He is Fabian Stokely,
postdoctoral researcher

00:21:14.420 --> 00:21:15.960
from Switzerland.

00:21:15.960 --> 00:21:21.710
And Fabian always wears
the same black tee shirt.

00:21:21.710 --> 00:21:29.600
And this guy is Christoph Paus,
my PhD supervisor from Germany.

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:34.110
And he flies between MIT
and CERN every other week.

00:21:34.110 --> 00:21:36.320
You might think, where's me?

00:21:36.320 --> 00:21:39.740
So this is me in the window.

00:21:39.740 --> 00:21:44.170
And I have to admit
that I didn't have time

00:21:44.170 --> 00:21:50.160
to brush teeth for months,
and I no longer care.

00:21:50.160 --> 00:21:53.250
There is dozens more
colleagues from MIT

00:21:53.250 --> 00:21:56.880
working on different Higgs
search channels, detector

00:21:56.880 --> 00:21:58.390
or computing.

00:21:58.390 --> 00:22:03.640
And they didn't care whether
I brushed teeth either.

00:22:03.640 --> 00:22:10.870
Well, you might want to ask, how
do you think about these days?

00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:14.400
There are [INAUDIBLE],
difficult to say.

00:22:14.400 --> 00:22:17.840
I wish I had invited
you to my office

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:21.520
at CERN Building
32, fourth floor.

00:22:21.520 --> 00:22:25.220
There's not much room, and if
you come during the summer,

00:22:25.220 --> 00:22:27.330
there's no air conditioner.

00:22:27.330 --> 00:22:30.740
And my desk is so small,
it can hold nothing

00:22:30.740 --> 00:22:34.320
but a few books and a laptop.

00:22:34.320 --> 00:22:36.950
However, look
through the window.

00:22:36.950 --> 00:22:39.760
This is the view
that you can see.

00:22:39.760 --> 00:22:44.880
And listen to the music that
[INAUDIBLE] the corridor.

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:49.570
And what I want to say can be
summarized as the following.

00:22:49.570 --> 00:22:55.340
Late night, look deep into
the sky, turn on music loudly,

00:22:55.340 --> 00:22:57.630
loudly, and sing along.

00:22:57.630 --> 00:23:01.812
Good time to free the
soul and face the unknown.

00:23:04.710 --> 00:23:08.020
As the night was
progressing, Christoph

00:23:08.020 --> 00:23:11.480
was about to catch
another flight.

00:23:11.480 --> 00:23:15.730
Having fixed some problem
in our computer cluster

00:23:15.730 --> 00:23:21.450
at MIT, important for producing
the final analysis results,

00:23:21.450 --> 00:23:24.430
Christoph was flying to
CERN for the unblinding

00:23:24.430 --> 00:23:28.630
event in the coming
afternoon, the event

00:23:28.630 --> 00:23:32.630
that unblinded search
results from all the channels

00:23:32.630 --> 00:23:36.380
were presented to the
entire CMS collaboration

00:23:36.380 --> 00:23:37.970
for the first time.

00:23:37.970 --> 00:23:42.750
I wrote down my memory
about that night.

00:23:42.750 --> 00:23:47.910
And the unblinding went in the
coming afternoon into my story.

00:23:47.910 --> 00:23:53.500
And I'd like to share
a little bit with you.

00:23:53.500 --> 00:23:56.810
I stayed in a room
of the CERN hostel

00:23:56.810 --> 00:24:01.060
last night, within three
minutes walk from my office,

00:24:01.060 --> 00:24:05.670
40 minutes walk from my studio
in St. Saint-Genis-Pouilly,

00:24:05.670 --> 00:24:09.850
a small town at the foot
of the Jura Mountains.

00:24:09.850 --> 00:24:12.880
The past couple
weeks was so intense

00:24:12.880 --> 00:24:19.350
that I almost live at CERN, with
few hours of sleep at the task,

00:24:19.350 --> 00:24:24.658
and 10 cups of coffee
many of the days.

00:24:24.658 --> 00:24:28.610
And since there was
almost no time to eat,

00:24:28.610 --> 00:24:32.370
there was no need
to brush teeth.

00:24:32.370 --> 00:24:36.990
Extremely tired, but
also extremely excited,

00:24:36.990 --> 00:24:41.740
I wrote down the slide-- title--
search for a standard model

00:24:41.740 --> 00:24:44.730
Higgs boson decaying to
two photons, unblinding.

00:24:47.240 --> 00:24:50.470
Representing the Higgs to
two-photon working group,

00:24:50.470 --> 00:24:54.660
I was going to unblind our
Higgs search results to the CMS

00:24:54.660 --> 00:24:58.750
collaboration in the coming
afternoon, the results still

00:24:58.750 --> 00:25:02.990
sitting in the dark
waiting to be uncovered.

00:25:02.990 --> 00:25:07.090
During the past year, I was
used to missing the last bus

00:25:07.090 --> 00:25:10.870
at 1:00 AM from CERN
to Saint-Genis-Pouilly

00:25:10.870 --> 00:25:15.310
and walking back along the
Jura Mountains onto the night.

00:25:15.310 --> 00:25:18.850
Sometimes the analysis
work got so busy

00:25:18.850 --> 00:25:22.320
that even such a walk
was not affordable.

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:26.600
Instead, I would stay at a desk
in my office over the night,

00:25:26.600 --> 00:25:30.260
or move to the CERN hostel
during the critical times,

00:25:30.260 --> 00:25:34.250
like this night, expecting
a couple of hours rest

00:25:34.250 --> 00:25:39.240
on the bed to refresh, but
still remaining at the desk

00:25:39.240 --> 00:25:41.710
the entire night.

00:25:41.710 --> 00:25:44.190
The staff at the
CERN hostel was used

00:25:44.190 --> 00:25:47.480
to my unexpected
interruptions and being

00:25:47.480 --> 00:25:49.530
able to find me a room.

00:25:49.530 --> 00:25:52.760
But no single room was
left for this night.

00:25:52.760 --> 00:25:55.300
All available was a double room.

00:25:55.300 --> 00:25:58.450
I paid for the room
without hesitation,

00:25:58.450 --> 00:26:00.420
not because I was rich.

00:26:00.420 --> 00:26:03.490
There was not much left of
a graduate student's center

00:26:03.490 --> 00:26:08.020
salary after paying the
rent, meal, and coffee.

00:26:08.020 --> 00:26:11.260
But the chance to work
together with these people,

00:26:11.260 --> 00:26:15.690
in this space, at this
time, towards these results,

00:26:15.690 --> 00:26:18.550
was only once.

00:26:18.550 --> 00:26:23.150
Even if I had to die
for the moment, I'd die.

00:26:23.150 --> 00:26:26.700
Everything else
is out of concern.

00:26:26.700 --> 00:26:31.190
The night deepened, floating
all the sleepless nights

00:26:31.190 --> 00:26:34.900
into the dark sky
towards the unknown.

00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:38.260
The slides grow within
the analysis descriptions

00:26:38.260 --> 00:26:41.690
and the validation plots,
reaching the black room

00:26:41.690 --> 00:26:43.590
for the final plots.

00:26:43.590 --> 00:26:47.610
The last round of cross checks
started between the two teams,

00:26:47.610 --> 00:26:52.140
with information flowing
through an email thread.

00:26:52.140 --> 00:26:56.070
Finally, the expected results
and the yields of photon pairs

00:26:56.070 --> 00:26:57.190
agreed.

00:26:57.190 --> 00:27:00.630
Time to look into
the signal region.

00:27:00.630 --> 00:27:04.830
Around 3:00 AM, both teams
unblinded the two-photon mass

00:27:04.830 --> 00:27:10.180
spectrum of the 2012
data-- clear excess jumping

00:27:10.180 --> 00:27:15.160
from the falling spectra of
multiple classes around 125

00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:19.650
GeV, about the same place
of the excess that we

00:27:19.650 --> 00:27:26.120
observed from the 2011 data.

00:27:26.120 --> 00:27:28.740
A real signal is there.

00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:32.770
It was not spoken
out, but I heard

00:27:32.770 --> 00:27:39.500
the yells bursting out from
the huts at different ends.

00:27:39.500 --> 00:27:46.110
Enormous excitement flowed out,
permeating silently in the air.

00:27:46.110 --> 00:27:49.040
I looked out through
the window into the sky

00:27:49.040 --> 00:27:52.770
with the speed of
light, but in the end,

00:27:52.770 --> 00:27:56.120
stood together with the
Grand Jura Mountains

00:27:56.120 --> 00:27:59.810
quietly upon the ground
watching the pairs

00:27:59.810 --> 00:28:03.295
of photons passing through
the light years of nights.

00:28:07.100 --> 00:28:09.780
Later in the morning,
we had a quick gathering

00:28:09.780 --> 00:28:11.820
together with more
colleagues from the Higgs

00:28:11.820 --> 00:28:16.150
to two-photon working group in
a small meeting room at CERN.

00:28:16.150 --> 00:28:18.820
Everybody looked
extremely excited,

00:28:18.820 --> 00:28:21.240
despite not sleeping much.

00:28:21.240 --> 00:28:23.610
We tried not to speak
loudly, since we

00:28:23.610 --> 00:28:26.000
had to keep the secret
until the unblinding

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.360
event in the afternoon.

00:28:28.360 --> 00:28:30.280
Still more plots to make.

00:28:30.280 --> 00:28:33.450
We soon went back to
work, with more colleagues

00:28:33.450 --> 00:28:36.880
from different teams
joining to help.

00:28:36.880 --> 00:28:41.130
At this time, all of the
huts were bumped together.

00:28:41.130 --> 00:28:46.600
I kept modifying the slides with
suggestions from my colleagues,

00:28:46.600 --> 00:28:51.730
while new plots continually come
of various statistical results

00:28:51.730 --> 00:28:57.450
or two-photon mass spectra being
updated with final granularity

00:28:57.450 --> 00:28:59.870
or refined style.

00:28:59.870 --> 00:29:02.870
As time approached
the unblinding event,

00:29:02.870 --> 00:29:05.780
I started putting the
final version of the plots

00:29:05.780 --> 00:29:08.320
from my colleagues
onto the page, one

00:29:08.320 --> 00:29:12.230
after another, each
plot a great trust

00:29:12.230 --> 00:29:15.780
falling silently upon my hut.

00:29:15.780 --> 00:29:17.690
Time passes 3:00 PM.

00:29:17.690 --> 00:29:21.690
I finally finished the
slides, with the last plot

00:29:21.690 --> 00:29:24.510
just assigned from Fabian.

00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:26.560
Our other colleagues,
after their super

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:30.210
quick and collaborative
effort, had

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:33.900
left earlier to the
unblinding event, which

00:29:33.900 --> 00:29:37.230
had already started at the
CERN building called Filtration

00:29:37.230 --> 00:29:38.770
Plant.

00:29:38.770 --> 00:29:44.230
Our channel was the second to
unblind, starting at 3:30 PM.

00:29:44.230 --> 00:29:47.520
We saved the slides
onto a flash disk

00:29:47.520 --> 00:29:51.650
and walked quickly towards
the conference room.

00:29:51.650 --> 00:29:53.780
So we arrived.

00:29:53.780 --> 00:29:56.690
Fabian opened the door.

00:29:56.690 --> 00:29:58.760
A hot current flowed out.

00:29:58.760 --> 00:30:02.650
The room was packed
with CMS colleagues.

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:05.290
All the seats were taken.

00:30:05.290 --> 00:30:10.950
Many colleagues sat on the
floor or stood against the wall.

00:30:10.950 --> 00:30:14.480
There are probably also hundreds
of colleagues connecting

00:30:14.480 --> 00:30:17.570
through the video link.

00:30:17.570 --> 00:30:20.960
Good luck, said he,
one of the good lucks

00:30:20.960 --> 00:30:26.190
I have received from my
colleagues since the morning.

00:30:26.190 --> 00:30:29.630
I carried the slides
and moved slowly

00:30:29.630 --> 00:30:32.680
through the field
of my colleagues.

00:30:32.680 --> 00:30:37.010
My body got heavier and
heavier as the lives

00:30:37.010 --> 00:30:40.640
of more and more people
connected to my own.

00:30:40.640 --> 00:30:44.520
My teammates always gave
me the strongest support,

00:30:44.520 --> 00:30:48.000
my Higgs to two photons
colleagues striving together

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:52.620
on the unblinding night,
and the entire group

00:30:52.620 --> 00:30:56.680
having worked extremely hard
together since last year.

00:30:56.680 --> 00:31:00.180
Representing them, I was going
to unblind our Higgs search

00:31:00.180 --> 00:31:02.170
results.

00:31:02.170 --> 00:31:05.370
The CMS colleagues, having
worked on different stages

00:31:05.370 --> 00:31:10.010
and aspects of the experiment
during the past 20 years,

00:31:10.010 --> 00:31:13.380
leading to the final data
analysis for the Higgs search

00:31:13.380 --> 00:31:18.620
from design, construction,
commission, to operation,

00:31:18.620 --> 00:31:23.580
from hardware, software, to
computing, from data taking,

00:31:23.580 --> 00:31:27.740
calibration, reconstruction,
to validation.

00:31:27.740 --> 00:31:30.410
The colleagues working on
the different Higgs search

00:31:30.410 --> 00:31:33.830
channels trying to
answer the same question,

00:31:33.830 --> 00:31:36.860
and the colleagues working on
the different physics topics,

00:31:36.860 --> 00:31:39.730
from the precision measurements
within the standard model

00:31:39.730 --> 00:31:42.130
to the search beyond
the standard model,

00:31:42.130 --> 00:31:45.420
all trying to deepen and
enlarge the same drawing

00:31:45.420 --> 00:31:47.700
of fundamental particle physics.

00:31:47.700 --> 00:31:52.110
Many of them were in this room
or on the video link waiting

00:31:52.110 --> 00:31:56.580
to see and to listen
to the results.

00:31:56.580 --> 00:31:59.300
The Atlas colleagues working
towards the same goal,

00:31:59.300 --> 00:32:02.950
the Large Hadron
Collider's providing

00:32:02.950 --> 00:32:08.410
the most powerful and
intense proton beans,

00:32:08.410 --> 00:32:10.660
the generations of
experimental particle

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:13.730
physicists search
for the Higgs boson,

00:32:13.730 --> 00:32:15.970
the theoretical
physicists whose work

00:32:15.970 --> 00:32:18.630
led to the prediction
of this particle

00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:23.440
about half a century ago,
and all the physicists

00:32:23.440 --> 00:32:26.610
from the experimental
and the theoretical sides

00:32:26.610 --> 00:32:29.520
working together to reach
the current understanding

00:32:29.520 --> 00:32:32.830
of the fundamental components
of matter and force

00:32:32.830 --> 00:32:37.960
over the past 100 years,
and all the human beings

00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:41.970
craving to understand
nature and ourselves,

00:32:41.970 --> 00:32:47.810
asking and searching across
the vast space and time.

00:32:47.810 --> 00:32:54.050
Some of us got together in
this space at this time.

00:32:54.050 --> 00:32:57.110
The Higgs to two photon
presentation was starting.

00:32:57.110 --> 00:32:59.610
My heart was beating violently.

00:32:59.610 --> 00:33:02.100
My mind was calm.

00:33:02.100 --> 00:33:07.500
Please, everybody, get ready
for the next 15 minutes.

00:33:07.500 --> 00:33:12.900
These 15 minutes would become
a part of our common memories.

00:33:12.900 --> 00:33:18.380
Please let me quickly show you a
couple of minutes from these 15

00:33:18.380 --> 00:33:19.410
minutes.

00:33:19.410 --> 00:33:23.815
Since there's no sound, so I'll
just to show you very quickly.

